# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-detection-response
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-detection-response/endpoint-detection-and-response] According to the *Endpoint Detection and Response - Global Market Outlook (2017-2026)* report, the adoption of cloud-based and on-premises EDR solutions are valued at USD 6.5 billion in 2025 and are expected to grow to USD 50.5 billion by 2034.
[src:network-detection-response/endpoint-detection-and-response] Endpoint detection and response technology is used to identify suspicious behavior and advanced persistent threats on endpoints in an environment, and alert administrators accordingly.
[src:network-detection-response/endpoint-detection-and-response] It does this by collecting and aggregating data from endpoints and other sources.
[src:network-detection-response/endpoint-detection-and-response] That data may or may not be enriched by additional cloud analysis.
[src:network-detection-response/endpoint-detection-and-response] EDR solutions are primarily an alerting tool rather than a protection layer but functions may be combined depending on the vendor.
[src:network-detection-response/endpoint-detection-and-response] The data may be stored in a centralized database or forwarded to a SIEM tool for cyber monitoring.
[src:network-detection-response/endpoint-detection-and-response] Every EDR platform has its unique set of capabilities.
[src:network-detection-response/endpoint-detection-and-response] Some vendors of EDR technologies leverage the free MITRE ATT&CK classification and framework for threats.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:network-detection-response/intrusion-detection-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Routers and switches that support NetFlow can collect IP traffic statistics on all interfaces where NetFlow is enabled, and later export those statistics as NetFlow records toward at least one NetFlow collector—typically a server that does the actual traffic analysis.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Note that the Egress interface, IP Nexthop or BGP Nexthops are not part of the key, and may not be accurate if the route changes before the expiration of the flow, or if load-balancing is done per-packet.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This definition of flows is also used for IPv6, and a similar definition is used for MPLS and Ethernet flows.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Advanced NetFlow or IPFIX implementations like Cisco Flexible NetFlow allow user-defined flow keys.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The router will output a flow record when it determines that the flow is finished.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] It does this by flow aging: when the router sees new traffic for an existing flow it resets the aging counter.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Also, TCP session termination in a TCP flow causes the router to expire the flow.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Routers can also be configured to output a flow record at a fixed interval even if the flow is still ongoing.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow records are traditionally exported using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and collected using a NetFlow collector.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The IP address of the NetFlow collector and the destination UDP port must be configured on the sending router.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] A common value is UDP port 2055, but other values like 9555 or 9995, 9025, 9026 etc. can also be used.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] For efficiency reasons, the router traditionally does not keep track of flow records already exported, so if a NetFlow packet is dropped due to network congestion or packet corruption, all contained records are lost forever.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The UDP protocol does not inform the router of the loss so it can send the packets again.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This can be a real problem, especially with NetFlow v8 or v9 that can aggregate a lot of packets or flows into a single record.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] A single UDP packet loss can cause a huge impact on the statistics of some flows.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] That is why some modern implementations of NetFlow use the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) to export packets so as to provide some protection against packet loss, and make sure that NetFlow v9 templates are received before any related record is exported.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Note that TCP would not be suitable for NetFlow because a strict ordering of packets would cause excessive buffering and delays.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The problem with SCTP is that it requires interaction between each NetFlow collector and each router exporting NetFlow.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] There may be performance limitations if a router has to deal with many NetFlow collectors, and a NetFlow collector has to deal with many routers, especially when some of them are unavailable due to failure or maintenance.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] SCTP may not be efficient if NetFlow must be exported toward several independent collectors, some of which may be test servers that can go down at any moment.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] UDP allows simple replication of NetFlow packets using Network taps or L2 or L3 Mirroring.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Simple stateless equipment can also filter or change the destination address of NetFlow UDP packets if necessary.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Since NetFlow export almost only use network backbone links, packet loss will often be negligible.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] If it happens, it will mostly be on the link between the network and the NetFlow collectors.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] A NetFlow record can contain a wide variety of information about the traffic in a given flow.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] For ICMP flows, the Source Port is zero, and the Destination Port number field codes ICMP message Type and Code (port = ICMP-Type * 256 + ICMP-Code) .
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The source and destination Autonomous System (AS) number fields can report the destination AS (last AS of AS-Path) or the immediate neighbor AS (first AS of AS-Path) depending on the router configuration.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] But the AS number will be zero if the feature is not supported, the route is unknown or not announced by BGP, or the AS is the local AS.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] There is no explicit way to distinguish between these cases.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] By analyzing flow data, a picture of traffic flow and traffic volume in a network can be built.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The NetFlow record format has evolved over time, hence the inclusion of version numbers.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Cisco maintains details of the different version numbers and the layout of the packets for each version.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow is usually enabled on a per-interface basis to limit load on the router components involved in NetFlow, or to limit the amount of NetFlow records exported.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow usually captures all packets received by an ingress IP interface, but some NetFlow implementations use IP filters to decide if a packet can be observed by NetFlow.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Some NetFlow implementations also allow the observation of packets on the egress IP interface, but this must be used with care: all flows from any ingress interface with NetFlow enabled to any interface with NetFlow enabled could be counted twice.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Standard NetFlow was designed to process all IP packets on an interface.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] But in some environments, e.g. on Internet backbones, that was too costly, due to the extra processing required for each packet, and large number of simultaneous flows.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] So Cisco introduced sampled NetFlow on Cisco 12000, and that is now used in all high-end routers that implement NetFlow.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Only one packet out of *n* is processed, where *n*, the sampling rate, is determined by the router configuration.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Some implementations have more complex methods to sample packets, like per-flow sampling on Cisco Catalysts.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The sampling rate is often the same for all interfaces, but can be adjusted per interface for some routers.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] When Sampled NetFlow is used, the NetFlow records must be adjusted for the effect of sampling - traffic volumes, in particular, are now an estimate rather than the actual measured flow volume.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow was initially implemented by Cisco, and described in an "informational" document that was not on the standards track: RFC 3954 – Cisco Systems NetFlow Services Export Version 9.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The NetFlow protocol itself has been superseded by Internet Protocol Flow Information eXport (IPFIX).
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Based on the NetFlow Version 9 implementation, IPFIX is on the IETF standards track with RFC 5101 (obsoleted by RFC 7011), RFC 5102 (obsoleted by RFC 7012), etc. which were published in 2008.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Many vendors other than Cisco provide similar network flow monitoring technology.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow may be a prevalent name in the area of flow monitoring, because of Cisco dominant market share in the networking industry.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Also flow-tools collection of software allows to process and manage NetFlow exports from Cisco and Juniper routers.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Introduced with the launch of the Cisco ASA 5580 products, NetFlow Security Event Logging utilizes NetFlow v9 fields and templates in order to efficiently deliver security telemetry in high performance environments.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow Security Event Logging scales better than syslog while offering the same level of detail and granularity in logged events.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow collection using standalone NetFlow probes is an alternative to flow collection from routers and switches.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This approach can overcome some limitations of router-based NetFlow monitoring.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The probes are transparently connected to the monitored link as a passive appliance using the TAP or SPAN port of the appliance.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Historically, NetFlow monitoring is easier to implement in a dedicated probe than in a router.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The easiest way to address the above drawbacks is to use a packet capture appliance inline in front of the router and capture all of the NetFlow output from the router.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This method allows for storage of large amount of NetFlow data (typically many years worth of data) and does not require reconfiguration of the network.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow collection from dedicated probes is well suited for observation of critical links, whereas NetFlow on routers provides a Network-wide view of the traffic that can be used for capacity planning, accounting, performance monitoring, and security.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] NetFlow was originally a Cisco packet switching technology for Cisco routers, implemented in IOS 11.x around 1996.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] It was originally a software implementation for the Cisco 7000, 7200 and 7500, where it was thought as an improvement over the then current Cisco Fast Switching.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Netflow was invented by Darren Kerr and Barry Bruin from Cisco (U.S. patent # 6,243,667 ).
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The idea was that the first packet of a flow would create a NetFlow switching record.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This record would then be used for all later packets of the same flow, until the expiration of the flow.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] Only the first packet of a flow would require an investigation of the route table to find the most specific matching route.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This is an expensive operation in software implementations, especially the old ones without Forwarding information base.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] The NetFlow switching record was actually some kind of route cache record, and old versions of IOS still refer to the NetFlow cache as **ip route-cache**.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This technology was advantageous for local networks.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This was especially true if some of the traffic had to be filtered by an ACL as only the first packet of a flow had to be evaluated by the ACL.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] As a switching technology, NetFlow was replaced around 1995 by Cisco Express Forwarding.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] This first appeared on Cisco 12000 routers, and later replaced NetFlow switching on advanced IOS for the Cisco 7200 and Cisco 7500.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] As of 2012, technologies similar to NetFlow switching are still in use in most firewalls and software-based IP routers.
[src:network-detection-response/netflow] For instance the conntrack feature of the Netfilter framework used by Linux.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NDR is delivered through a combination of hardware and software sensors, along with a software or SaaS management console.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] Organizations use NDR to detect and contain malicious post-breach activity such as ransomware or insider malicious activity.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NDR focuses on identifying abnormal behavior patterns and anomalies rather than relying solely on signature-based threat detection.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] This allows NDR to spot weak signals and unknown threats from network traffic, like lateral movement or data exfiltration.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NDR provides visibility into network activities to identify anomalies using machine learning algorithms.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] The automated response capabilities can help reduce the workload for security teams.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NDR also assists incident responders with threat hunting by supplying context and analysis.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] Deployment options include physical or virtual sensors.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] Sensors are typically out-of-band, positioned to monitor network flows without impacting performance.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] Cloud-based NDR options integrate with IaaS providers to gain visibility across hybrid environments.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] Ongoing tuning helps reduce false positives.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NDR competes against broader platforms like SIEM and XDR for security budgets.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NDR can be used to complement EDR's blind spot.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] The origins of NDR trace back to network traffic analysis (NTA) solutions that emerged around 2019.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NTA provided greater visibility into network activities to quickly identify and respond to potential threats.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] By 2020, NTA adoption was growing for real-time threat detection.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] That year, a study found that 87% of organizations used NTA, with 43% considering it a "first line of defense".
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] The NTA market was valued at US$2.9 billion in 2022, and expected to reach US$8.5 billion by 2032.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NTA evolved into NDR as a distinct product category.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] NDR combined detection capabilities with incident response workflows.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] This enabled detecting and reacting to threats across networks in real time.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] Major attacks like WannaCry in 2017 and the SolarWinds breach in 2020 highlighted the need for solutions like NDR.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] Traditional perimeter defenses and signature-based tools proved insufficient against modern threats.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] The use of artificial intelligence in NDR tools is growing, as security teams explore AI's potential to enhance NDR capabilities.
[src:network-detection-response/network-detection-and-response] According to Gartner, NDR vendors include Vectra AI, Darktrace, ExtraHop, Corelight, Trend Micro, Trellix, Arista Networks, Cisco, LinkShadow Fortinet, IronNet, MixMode, Plixer.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM tools can be implemented as software, hardware, or managed services.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems log security events and generate reports to meet regulatory frameworks such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS).
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] The integration of SIM and SEM within SIEM provides organizations with a centralized approach for monitoring security events and responding to threats in real-time.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] In recent years, SIEM has become increasingly incorporated into national cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] For instance, Executive Order 14028 signed in 2021 by U.S.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden mandates the use of SIEM technologies to improve incident detection and reporting in federal systems.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Compliance with these mandates is further reinforced by frameworks such as NIST SP 800-92, which outlines best practices for managing computer security logs.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms are aggregating and normalizing data not only from various Information Technology (IT) sources, but from production and manufacturing Operational Technology (OT) environments as well.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Initially, system logging was primarily used for troubleshooting and debugging.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] However, as operating systems and networks have grown more complex, so has the generation of system logs.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] The monitoring of system logs has also become increasingly common due to the rise of sophisticated cyberattacks and the need for compliance with regulatory frameworks, which mandate logging security controls within risk management frameworks (RMF).
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Starting in the late 1970s, working groups began establishing criteria for managing auditing and monitoring programs, laying the groundwork for modern cybersecurity practices, such as insider threat detection and incident response.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] A key publication during this period was NIST’s Special Publication 500-19.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] In 2005, the term "SIEM" (Security Information and Event Management) was introduced by Gartner analysts Mark Nicolett and Amrit Williams.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems provide a single interface for gathering security data from information systems and presenting it as actionable intelligence.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] With the implementation of RMFs globally, auditing and monitoring have become central to information assurance and security.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Cybersecurity professionals now rely on logging data to perform real-time security functions, driven by governance models that incorporate these processes into analytical tasks.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] As information assurance matured in the late 1990s and into the 2000s, the need to centralize system logs became apparent.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Centralized log management allows for easier oversight and coordination across networked systems.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden signed Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity," which established further logging requirements, including audit logging and endpoint protection, to enhance incident response capabilities.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] This order was a response to an increase in ransomware attacks targeting critical infrastructure.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] By reinforcing information assurance controls within RMFs, the order aimed to drive compliance and secure funding for cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Published in September 2006, the NIST SP 800-92 Guide to Computer Security Log Management serves as a key document within the NIST Risk Management Framework to guide what should be auditable.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] As indicated by the absence of the term "SIEM", the document was released before the widespread adoption of SIEM technologies.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Although the guide is not exhaustive due to rapid changes in technology since its publication, it remains relevant by anticipating industry growth.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] NIST is not the only source of guidance on regulatory mechanisms for auditing and monitoring, and many organizations are encouraged to adopt SIEM solutions rather than relying solely on host-based checks.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Public and private organizations frequently reference NIST documents in their security policies.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 AU-2 Event Monitoring is a key security control that supports system auditing and ensures continuous monitoring for information assurance and cybersecurity operations.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions are typically employed as central tools for these efforts.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Federal systems categorized based on their impact on confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) have five specific logging requirements (AU-2 a-e) that must be met.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] While logging every action is possible, it is generally not recommended due to the volume of logs and the need for actionable security data.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] AU-2 provides a foundation for organizations to build a logging strategy that aligns with other controls.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 SI-4 System Monitoring outlines the requirements for monitoring systems, including detecting unauthorized access and tracking anomalies, malware, and potential attacks.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] This security control specifies both the hardware and software requirements for detecting suspicious activities.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, NIST SP 800-53 RA-10 Threat Hunting, added in Revision 5, emphasizes proactive network defense by identifying threats that evade traditional controls.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions play a critical role in aggregating security information for threat hunting teams.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Together, AU-2, SI-4, and RA-10 demonstrate how NIST controls integrate into a comprehensive security strategy.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] These controls, supported by SIEM solutions, help ensure continuous monitoring, risk assessments, and in-depth defense mechanisms across federal and private networks.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] In practice many products in this area will have a mix of these functions, so there will often be some overlap – and many commercial vendors also promote their own terminology.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Oftentimes commercial vendors provide different combinations of these functionalities which tend to improve SIEM overall.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Log management alone doesn't provide real-time insights on network security, SEM on its own won't provide complete data for deep threat analysis.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] When SEM and log management are combined, more information is available for SIEM to monitor.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] A key focus is to monitor and help manage user and service privileges, directory services and other system-configuration changes; as well as providing log auditing and review and incident response.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM architectures may vary by vendor; however, generally, essential components comprise the SIEM engine.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] A basic SIEM infrastructure is depicted in the image to the right.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Computer security researcher Chris Kubecka identified the following SIEM use cases, presented at the hacking conference 28C3 (Chaos Communication Congress).
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms support not only detection, but response too.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] The response can be manual or automated including AI based response.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems play a significant role in helping organizations meet regulatory compliance requirements by centralizing log collection, enabling real-time monitoring, and generating audit-ready reports.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, covered entities must implement audit controls that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to security incidents within 24 hours, a capability commonly provided by SIEM platforms.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data, with SIEM systems commonly used to aggregate and analyze the required log data across distributed environments.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires organizations to maintain audit trails for financial system access, and SIEM platforms provide the centralized logging and retention capabilities necessary to demonstrate compliance during audits.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems can have hundreds and thousands of correlation rules.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Some of these are simple, and some are more complex.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Once a correlation rule is triggered the system can take appropriate steps to mitigate a cyber attack.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Usually, this includes sending a notification to a user and then possibly limiting or even shutting down the system.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Brute force detection is relatively straightforward.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Brute forcing relates to continually trying to guess a variable.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] It most commonly refers to someone trying to constantly guess your password - either manually or with a tool.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] However, it can refer to trying to guess URLs or important file locations on your system.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] An automated brute force is easy to detect as someone trying to enter their password 60 times in a minute is impossible.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] When a user logs in to a system, generally speaking, it creates a timestamp of the event.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Alongside the time, the system may often record other useful information such as the device used, physical location, IP address, incorrect login attempts, etc.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] The more data is collected the more use can be gathered from it.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] For impossible travel, the system looks at the current and last login date/time and the difference between the recorded distances.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] If it deems it's not possible for this to happen, for example traveling hundreds of miles within a minute, then it will set off a warning.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Many employees and users are now using VPN services which may obscure physical location.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] This should be taken into consideration when setting up such a rule.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] The average user does not typically copy or move files on the system repeatedly.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Thus, any excessive file copying on a system could be attributed to an attacker wanting to cause harm to an organization.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Unfortunately, it's not as simple as stating someone has gained access to your network illegally and wants to steal confidential information.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] It could also be an employee looking to sell company information, or they could just want to take home some files for the weekend.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Monitoring network traffic against unusual patterns that includes any threats or attacks ranging from DDOS to network scans.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Note SIEM can monitor data flow in the network and to detect and prevent potential data exfiltration efforts.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] In general dedicated Data loss prevention (DLP) take care about data loss prevention.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS (distributed denial of service) attack could cause significant damage to a company or organization.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS attack can not only take a website offline, it can also make a system weaker.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] With suitable correlation rules in place, a SIEM should trigger an alert at the start of the attack so that the company can take the necessary precautionary measures to protect vital systems.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] File integrity and change monitoring (FIM) is the process of monitoring the files on your system.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Unexpected changes in your system files will trigger an alert as it's a likely indication of a cyber attack.
[src:network-detection-response/security-information-and-event-management] Some examples of customized rules to alert on event conditions involve user authentication rules, attacks detected and infections detected.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] Zeek's purpose is to inspect network traffic and generate a variety of logs describing the activity it sees.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] A complete list of log files is available at the project documentation site.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] One of Zeek's primary use cases involves cyber threat hunting.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] The principal author, Paxson, originally named the software "Bro" as a warning regarding George Orwell's Big Brother from the novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] In 2018 the project leadership team decided to rename the software.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] At LBNL in the 1990s, the developers ran their sensors as a pseudo-user named "zeek", thereby inspiring the name change in 2018.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] Security teams identify locations on their network where they desire visibility.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] They deploy one or more network taps or enable switch SPAN ports for port mirroring to gain access to traffic.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] They deploy Zeek on servers with access to those visibility points.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] The Zeek software on the server deciphers network traffic as logs, writing them to local disk or remote storage.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] Zeek's event engine analyzes live or recorded network traffic to generate neutral event logs.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] Zeek uses common ports and dynamic protocol detection (involving signatures as well as behavioral analysis) to identify network protocols.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] Developers write Zeek policy scripts in the Turing complete Zeek scripting language.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] By default Zeek logs information about events to files, but analysts can also configure Zeek to take other actions, such as sending an email, raising an alert, executing a system command, updating an internal metric, or calling another Zeek script.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] Zeek analyzers perform application layer decoding, anomaly detection, signature matching and connection analysis.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] Zeek's developers designed the software to incorporate additional analyzers.
[src:network-detection-response/zeek] The latest method for creating new protocol analyzers relies on the Spicy framework.
